children.text: The ventilation openings provided in this sub-floor are not spaced evenly, resulting in a damp environment, which according to the BCA, encourages timber rot, fungus growth and the potential for termite activity.
Part 3.4.1.2 of the National Construction Code’s Building Code of Australia (BCA) states that
‘Subfloor spaces must be provided with openings in external walls and internal subfloor walls in accordance with Table 3.4.1.1’,
‘a subfloor space must contain no dead air spaces; and have openings evenly spaced as far as practicable’.

As there is no practical reason that these ventilation openings cannot be evenly spaced, the builder will need to properly rectify the ventilation to ensure there are no dead air spaces in accordance with part 3.4.1.2 of the BCA.
